questions_and_answers.question: What does this excerpt from Shakespeare's "Twelfth Night" reveal about Duke Orsino?
questions_and_answers.answer: I'm guessing you mean this excerpt: "If music be the food of love, play on, Give me excess of it; that, surfeiting, The appetite may sicken and so die.— That strain again;—it had a dying fall; O, it came o'er my ear like the sweet south, That breathes upon a bank of violets, Stealing and giving odour.—Enough; no more; 'Tis not so sweet now as it was before." • *If so, then after you read the excerpt you will find that Duke Orsino was in love with love itself. **

questions_and_answers.question: What does this excerpt from Shakespeare's Twelfth Night reveal about Duke Orsino? A. He has developed a dislike for music. B. He is in love with the idea of love itself. C. He has lost his appetite for food. D. He wants sweet flowers in his court.
questions_and_answers.answer: B. He is in love with the idea of love itself.

questions_and_answers.answer: What this excerpt from Shakespeare’s Twelfth Night reveals about Duke Orsino is that B) He is in love with the idea of love itself. By using the system of elimination, you can come to this solution. He hasn't developed a dislike for music, and this excerpt deals with his ideas about love, which means that C and D are also incorrect. B is because he thought he was truly in love, but realized he is in love with the idea of being in love.

text_blocks.snippet: In Twelfth Night, Duke Orsino's opening lines, "If music be the food of love, play on," reveal him as a romantic and perhaps melodramatic character, deeply invested in the idea of love as an all-consuming force. He seems more in love with the idea of love than with the person of Olivia, seeking emotional intensity and indulgence. His desire for music, and then his subsequent request to stop, shows a fickle and perhaps self-indulgent nature.
snippet_highlighted_words: a romantic and perhaps melodramatic character, deeply invested in the idea of love as an all-consuming force

text_blocks.snippet: Here's a breakdown of what the excerpt reveals:

list.title: Romantic Idealism:
list.snippet: Orsino's first line suggests a romantic disposition, viewing music as the sustenance of love.

list.title: Desire for Excess:
list.snippet: He asks for excessive amounts of music, indicating a desire to be overwhelmed by his emotions.

list.title: Fickleness:
list.snippet: The immediate shift to wanting the music to stop reveals a potential for changing moods and a lack of sustained focus.

list.title: Melancholy:
list.snippet: The lines also suggest a melancholic temperament, as he wallows in his unrequited love for Olivia.

list.title: Self-Absorption:
list.snippet: His focus on his own emotional state and his rather dramatic pronouncements hint at a degree of self-absorption.

list.title: Metaphorical Language:
list.snippet: Orsino's use of metaphors (like the "dying fall" of the music and the "hart" being hunted by hounds) further highlights his romantic sensibility and his inclination to express himself through heightened language.
